{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   7. FAQ — Editorial accordion
   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
<section class="ep-faq">
  <div class="ep-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="ep-chapter-label">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="ep-faq-title">Annuity FAQ</h2>
      <p class="ep-faq-sub">Get straight answers about annuities from a fiduciary advisor.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="ep-btn-ghost">Schedule Annuity Review</a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What is a fixed index annuity? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>A fixed index annuity links returns to a stock market index (like the S&P 500) but protects your principal from losses. You get a portion of market gains (subject to caps and participation rates) but never lose money in down years. They're complex products with varying fees and features that should be carefully evaluated. Guarantees are subject to the claims-paying ability of the issuing insurance company.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Are annuities a good investment? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Annuities aren't investments — they're insurance products designed to provide guaranteed income. They can be appropriate if you need income protection and don't have a pension, but they often come with high fees, limited liquidity, and surrender charges. The key is determining if the guaranteed income feature is worth the trade-offs for your specific situation.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What fees do annuities have? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Annuity fees vary widely. Variable annuities typically charge 2-3% annually (mortality and expense charges, investment fees, rider fees). Fixed and fixed index annuities may have lower annual fees but often include surrender charges (penalties for early withdrawal) that can last 5-10 years. We help you understand the total cost structure before you commit.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Can I get out of an annuity? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Yes, but it may be expensive. Most annuities have surrender charges that decrease over time (often 5-10 years). You may also owe taxes and IRS penalties if you're under 59½. We review your existing annuity to determine if it makes sense to exit, stay in, or modify it through available options like 1035 exchanges.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When does an annuity make sense? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Annuities can make sense if you need guaranteed lifetime income and don't have a pension, want to transfer longevity risk to an insurance company, or need a simple income solution in retirement. They typically DON'T make sense if you need liquidity, have low risk tolerance but high fees, or already have sufficient guaranteed income from Social Security and pensions. Every situation is different — we analyze yours specifically.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What's the difference between immediate and deferred annuities? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>An immediate annuity (SPIA) starts paying income within a year of purchase — you trade a lump sum for guaranteed lifetime payments. A deferred annuity (including DIAs) delays income to a future date, allowing the principal to grow tax-deferred. Immediate annuities work well for those who need income now, while deferred annuities are better for those planning income needs 5-10+ years out.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Should I buy an annuity inside my IRA? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Usually no. IRAs already have tax-deferred growth, so adding an annuity inside an IRA duplicates that benefit while adding fees and restrictions. The main reason to use an annuity in an IRA is for the guaranteed income feature, not tax deferral. If you don't need guaranteed income, a diversified portfolio inside the IRA is typically more cost-effective and flexible.</p></div>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

